<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n54126d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54126d">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54126d"> 126(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> shut up your / wit</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&lsquo;Very fine,&rsquo; said the Dean, &lsquo;I have got much by complaining to you, to have all your wife&apos;s Faults laid at my door.&rsquo; &lsquo;Well, Sir,&rsquo; said I, &lsquo;all these misdemeanoirs may be included under the article of <i>Pride</i>: now let me know my other Crime:&rsquo; &lsquo;Why,&rsquo; said he, &lsquo;you can&apos;t walk fast; but at present, I excuse you.&rsquo; &lsquo;Well, Sir, if I can&apos;t mend my pride, I&apos;ll try to mend my pace.&rsquo; &lsquo;Mr. Pilkington,&rsquo; said he, &lsquo;I have a mind to clip your wife&apos;s <mark>wit</mark>.&rsquo; &lsquo;Indeed, Sir,&rsquo; said I, &lsquo;that&apos;s death by law, for &apos;tis sterling.&rsquo; &lsquo;<mark>Shut up your mouth</mark>, for all day, Letty,&rsquo; said Mr. Pilkington, &lsquo;for that answer is real wit.&rsquo; &lsquo;Nay,&rsquo; said the Dean, &lsquo;I believe we had better shut up our own, for at this rate she&apos;ll be too many for us.&rsquo; I am sure, if I was not proud before, this was enough to make me so. <small> Letitia Pilkington, <a name="MMLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MMLP"><cite title="source">Memoirs</cite></a> (1928) 66-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
